## Ethnic group and nation

For other uses, see [Greeks (disambiguation)](/Greeks_(disambiguation)).

The term "Grecian" redirects here. For other uses, see [Grecian (disambiguation)](/Grecian_(disambiguation)).

### Ethnic group

**Greeks** (also known as **Hellenes**; in [Greek](/Greek_language): Έλληνες, *Éllines*) are an [ethnic group](/Ethnic_group) and [nation](/Nation) indigenous to the geographical regions of [Greece](/Greece), [Cyprus](/Greek_Cypriots), [southern Albania](/Greeks_in_Albania), [Anatolia](/Greeks_in_Turkey), certain areas of [Italy](/Greeks_in_Italy) and [Egypt](/Egyptian_Greeks), and to a lesser extent, other nations bordering the [Eastern Mediterranean](/Eastern_Mediterranean) and the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea). A significant [diaspora](/Greek_diaspora) (known as *omogenia*) also exists, with numerous Greek communities established globally.

Historically, Greek colonies and communities were established along the shores of the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea) and the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea). However, the heartland of the Greek people has consistently been the [Aegean](/Aegean_Sea) and [Ionian](/Ionian_Sea) seas, where the [Greek language](/Greek_language) has been spoken continuously since the [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age). Up until the early 20th century, Greeks were distributed across the [Greek peninsula](/Greek_peninsula), the western coast of [Asia Minor](/Anatolia), the Black Sea coast, [Cappadocia](/Cappadocia) in central Anatolia, [Egypt](/Egypt), the [Balkans](/Balkans), Cyprus, and [Constantinople](/Constantinople). Many of these regions largely corresponded with the territories of the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) in the late 11th century and the Eastern Mediterranean areas of ancient [Greek colonization](/Greek_colonies). Key cultural centers for the Greeks have included [Athens](/Athens), [Thessalonica](/Thessalonica), [Alexandria](/Alexandria), [Smyrna](/Smyrna), and [Constantinople](/Constantinople) at various points in history.

In contemporary times, the majority of ethnic Greeks reside within the borders of the modern Greek state or in Cyprus. The [Greek genocide](/Greek_genocide) and the subsequent [population exchange between Greece and Turkey](/Population_exchange_between_Greece_and_Turkey) effectively brought an end to the three-millennia-old Greek presence in Asia Minor. Other long-standing Greek populations can be found from southern Italy to the Caucasus, and in southern [Russia](/Greeks_in_Russia) and [Ukraine](/Greeks_in_Ukraine), as well as in [Greek diaspora](/Greek_diaspora) communities across numerous other countries. Today, the vast majority of Greeks officially identify with the [Greek Orthodox Church](/Greek_Orthodox_Church).

The Greeks have made profound contributions and exerted significant influence on culture, visual arts, exploration, theatre, literature, philosophy, ethics, politics, architecture, music, mathematics, [medicine](/Ancient_Greek_medicine), science, technology, commerce, cuisine, and sports. The [Greek language](/Greek_language) stands as the oldest recorded living language, and its vocabulary has formed the basis for many other languages, including [English](/English_words_of_Greek_origin) and [international scientific nomenclature](/International_scientific_vocabulary). Greek served as the primary [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) in the Mediterranean world from the 4th century BC onwards, and the [New Testament](/New_Testament) of the [Christian Bible](/Bible) was originally composed in Greek.

