### Identity

The terminology used to define "Greekness" has varied throughout history but has never been exclusively limited to, or entirely identified with, citizenship in a Greek state. [Herodotus](/Herodotus), in his seminal work, provided a well-known account of what constituted Greek (Hellenic) ethnic identity in his time, enumerating the following key elements:

*   Shared [descent](/Kinship_and_descent) (*hómaimon*, 'of the same blood')
*   Shared [language](/Language) (*homóglōsson*, 'speaking the same tongue')
*   Shared [sanctuaries](/Sanctuaries) and [sacrifices](/Sacrifices) (*theôn hidrúmatá te koinà kaì thusíai*, 'common foundations, common sacrifices to gods')
*   Shared [customs](/Mores) (*ḗthea homótropa*, 'customs of like fashion')

By Western standards, the term "Greeks" has traditionally encompassed all native speakers of the [Greek language](/Greek_language), regardless of whether they spoke [Mycenaean](/Mycenaean_Greek_language), [Byzantine](/Medieval_Greek), or [modern Greek](/Modern_Greek). [Byzantine Greeks](/Byzantine_Greeks) identified themselves as *Romaioi* ("Romans"), *Graikoi* ("Greeks"), and *Christianoi* ("Christians"), reflecting their inheritance of [imperial Rome](/Roman_Empire), their descent from their [classical Greek forebears](/Ancient_Greeks), and their adherence to the [Apostles](/Apostles_in_the_New_Testament). During the mid-to-late Byzantine period (11th–13th centuries), an increasing number of Byzantine Greek intellectuals identified as *Hellenes*, although for the majority of Greek speakers, "Hellene" still retained its association with paganism. On the eve of the [Fall of Constantinople](/Fall_of_Constantinople), the [Last Emperor](/Constantine_XI) urged his soldiers to remember their lineage as descendants of Greeks and Romans.

Prior to the establishment of the modern Greek nation-state, the connection between ancient and modern Greeks was particularly emphasized by the scholars of the Greek Enlightenment, most notably Rigas Feraios. In his "Political Constitution," he addressed the nation as "the people descendant of the Greeks." The [modern Greek state](/History_of_Modern_Greece) was established in 1829, when the Greeks liberated a portion of their ancestral homelands, the [Peloponnese](/Peloponnese), from the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire). The extensive [Greek diaspora](/Greek_diaspora) and the influential merchant class played a crucial role in disseminating the ideas of Western [romantic nationalism](/Romantic_nationalism) and [philhellenism](/Philhellenism). These, combined with the concept of Hellenism formulated during the final centuries of the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire), formed the bedrock of the [Diafotismos](/Diafotismos) and the contemporary understanding of Hellenism.

Present-day Greeks constitute a nation in the sense of an [ethnos](/Ethnic_group), defined by their possession of [Greek culture](/Culture_of_Greece) and their Greek [mother tongue](/First_language), rather than by citizenship, race, or religion, or by allegiance to any specific state. In ancient and medieval times, and to some extent still today, the Greek term was *genos*, which also denotes common ancestry.

***

### Names

Greeks and Greek speakers have employed various names to refer to themselves collectively. The term Achaeans (Ἀχαιοί) is one of the [collective names](/Names_of_the_Greeks) for the Greeks found in [Homer's](/Homer) [Iliad](/Iliad) and [Odyssey](/Odyssey). The Homeric "long-haired Achaeans" are understood to have been part of the [Mycenaean civilization](/Mycenaean_civilization) that dominated Greece from approximately 1600 BC to 1100 BC. Other common names used are Danaans (Δαναοί) and Argives (Ἀργεῖοι), while Panhellenes (Πανέλληνες) and Hellenes (Ἕλληνες) each appear only once in the Iliad. In historical contexts, all these terms were used synonymously to denote a unified Greek identity. Herodotus identified the [Achaeans](/Achaea_(ancient_region)) of the northern [Peloponnese](/Peloponnese) as descendants of the earlier, Homeric Achaeans.

[Homer](/Homer) refers to the "Hellenes" as a relatively small tribe settled in the Thessalian region of [Phthia](/Phthia), whose warriors were led by [Achilleus](/Achilleus). The [Parian Chronicle](/Parian_Chronicle) states that Phthia was the ancestral homeland of the Hellenes and that this name was bestowed upon those previously known as Greeks (Γραικοί). In [Greek mythology](/Greek_mythology), [Hellen](/Hellen), the patriarch of the Hellenes who ruled around Phthia, was the son of [Pyrrha](/Pyrrha) and [Deucalion](/Deucalion), the sole survivors of the [Great Deluge](/Flood_myth). The Greek philosopher [Aristotle](/Aristotle) identifies ancient [Hellas](/Ancient_Greece) as a region in [Epirus](/Epirus) situated between [Dodona](/Dodona) and the [Achelous](/Achelous) river, the site of Deucalion's Great Deluge. This land was occupied by the [Selloi](/Selloi) and the "Greeks" who subsequently became known as "Hellenes." In the Homeric tradition, the Selloi were the priests of the Dodonian Zeus.

In the [Hesiodic](/Hesiod) [Catalogue of Women](/Catalogue_of_Women), [Graecus](/Graecus) is presented as the son of Zeus and [Pandora II](/Pandora_II), the sister of Hellen, the patriarch of the Hellenes. According to the [Parian Chronicle](/Parian_Chronicle), when [Deucalion](/Deucalion) became king of Phthia, the Graikoi (Γραικοί) were renamed Hellenes. [Aristotle](/Aristotle), in his *Meteorologica*, notes that the Hellenes were related to the Graikoi.

#### Etymology

The English terms "Greece" and "Greek" are derived, via the Latin *Graecia* and *Graecus*, from the name of the [Graeci](/Graecians) (Γραικοί, *Graikoí*; singular Γραικός, *Graikós*). These were among the first [ancient Greek tribes](/List_of_ancient_Greek_tribes) to settle in [southern Italy](/Southern_Italy), an area known as "[Magna Graecia](/Magna_Graecia)". The term possibly originates from the [Proto-Indo-European](/Proto-Indo-European_language) root *ǵerh₂-*, meaning "to grow old," more specifically from [Graea](/Graea), an ancient city identified by [Aristotle](/Aristotle) as the oldest in Greece and the source of colonists for the [Naples](/Naples) area.

***

### Continuity

The most evident link connecting modern and ancient Greeks is their language, which boasts a documented tradition spanning at least from the 14th century BC to the present day, albeit with a hiatus during the [Greek Dark Ages](/Greek_Dark_Ages) (11th–8th centuries BC), a period for which written records are absent (though the [Cypriot syllabary](/Cypriot_syllabary) was in use during this time). Scholars often compare the continuity of this linguistic tradition to that of the [Chinese language](/Chinese_language) alone. Since its inception, Hellenism has primarily been defined by shared culture, and the national continuity of the Greek world is far more certain than its demographic trajectory. Yet, Hellenism also encompassed an ancestral dimension, notably through aspects of Athenian literature that influenced concepts of descent based on autochthony. During the later periods of the Eastern Roman Empire, regions such as [Ionia](/Ionia) and [Constantinople](/Constantinople) experienced a Hellenic revival in language, philosophy, and literature, drawing inspiration from classical models of thought and scholarship. This resurgence significantly bolstered the sense of cultural affinity with ancient Greece and its classical heritage. Throughout their history, the Greeks have maintained their language and [alphabet](/Greek_alphabet), certain values and cultural traditions, customs, a sense of religious and cultural distinction and exclusion (the term [barbarian](/Barbarian) was used by the 12th-century historian [Anna Komnene](/Anna_Komnene) to describe non-Greek speakers), and a unified sense of Greek identity and ethnicity, despite the undeniable socio-political transformations of the past two millennia. Recent anthropological studies analyzing both ancient and modern Greek osteological samples have indicated bio-genetic affinity and continuity between these groups, suggesting a direct genetic link between ancient and modern Greeks.

***

### Demographics

Currently, Greeks form the majority ethnic group in the [Hellenic Republic](/Hellenic_Republic), constituting 93% of the country's population. In the [Republic of Cyprus](/Republic_of_Cyprus), they represent 78% of the island's population, excluding Turkish settlers in the occupied territories. Greek populations have historically not exhibited high rates of growth; a significant portion of population growth in Greece since its establishment in 1832 has been attributed to the annexation of new territories and the influx of 1.5 million Greek refugees following the [1923 population exchange](/Population_exchange_between_Greece_and_Turkey) between Greece and Turkey. Approximately 80% of Greece's population resides in urban areas, with 28% concentrated in Athens.

Greek Cypriots share a similar pattern of emigration, typically towards English-speaking countries due to the island's colonization by the [British Empire](/British_Empire). Waves of [emigration](/Emigration) followed the [Turkish invasion of Cyprus](/Turkish_invasion_of_Cyprus) in 1974, and the population experienced a decline between mid-1974 and 1977 due to emigration, war casualties, and a temporary decrease in fertility. Following the [ethnic cleansing](/Ethnic_cleansing) of one-third of the island's Greek population in 1974, there was an increase in Greek Cypriots leaving, particularly for the Middle East, which contributed to a population decrease that eventually stabilized in the 1990s. Today, more than two-thirds of the Greek population in Cyprus lives in urban areas.

Around 1990, most Western estimates placed the number of ethnic Greeks in Albania at approximately 200,000; however, during the 1990s, a majority of them migrated to Greece. The Greek minority in [Turkey](/Greeks_in_Turkey), which numbered over 200,000 after the 1923 exchange, has now dwindled to a few thousand, following the 1955 [Constantinople Pogrom](/Istanbul_Pogrom) and other instances of state-sponsored violence and discrimination. This effectively, though not entirely, concluded the three-thousand-year presence of Hellenism in Asia Minor. Smaller Greek minorities exist in the remaining Balkan countries, the [Levant](/Greeks_in_Lebanon), and the [Black Sea](/Greeks_in_Georgia) states, representing remnants of the old [Greek Diaspora](/Greek_Diaspora) (pre-19th century).

***

### Diaspora

The precise number of Greeks residing outside Greece and Cyprus today is a subject of debate. Where census data is available, it indicates around three million Greeks living outside these two countries. Estimates provided by the [SAE – World Council of Hellenes Abroad](/SAE_%E2%80%93_World_Council_of_Hellenes_Abroad) suggest a figure closer to seven million worldwide. According to George Prevelakis of [Sorbonne University](/Sorbonne_University), the number is nearer to just under five million. Factors such as integration, intermarriage, and language loss influence the self-identification of the Greek diaspora (*omogenia*). Significant centers of diaspora communities include [New York City](/Greek_Americans), [Chicago](/Chicago), [Boston](/Boston), [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), [Sydney](/Greek_Australian), [Melbourne](/Greek_community_of_Melbourne), [London](/Greeks_in_the_United_Kingdom), [Toronto](/Greek_community_of_Toronto), [Montreal](/Greek_Canadian), [Vancouver](/Vancouver), [Auckland](/Greek_New_Zealander), and [Sao Paulo](/Greek_Brazilian). In 2010, the Hellenic Parliament introduced legislation enabling members of the diaspora to vote in Greek elections; this law was repealed in early 2014.

#### Ancient

In antiquity, the trading and colonizing activities of Greek tribes and city-states disseminated Greek culture, religion, and language throughout the Mediterranean and Black Sea basins. This was particularly evident in [Southern Italy](/Southern_Italy) (the region known as "[Magna Graecia](/Magna_Graecia)"), Spain, the [south of France](/History_of_Marseille), and along the [Black Sea coasts](/Pontian_Greeks). Under Alexander the Great's empire and its successor states, Greek and Hellenizing ruling classes were established in the [Middle East](/Seleucid_Kingdom), [India](/Indo-Greek_Kingdom), and [Egypt](/Ptolemaic_dynasty). The [Hellenistic period](/Hellenistic_period) is distinguished by a new wave of Greek colonization, which led to the establishment of Greek cities and kingdoms in [Asia](/Dayuan) and [Africa](/Cyrene,_Libya). During the Roman Empire, increased ease of travel facilitated the spread of Greeks across the Empire, and in the eastern territories, Greek supplanted [Latin](/Latin) as the dominant [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca). The modern-day [Griko community](/Griko_people) in southern Italy, numbering approximately 60,000, may represent a living vestige of the ancient Greek populations of Italy.

#### Modern

During and in the aftermath of the [Greek War of Independence](/Greek_War_of_Independence), Greeks from the diaspora played a crucial role in the establishment of the nascent state, raising funds and fostering awareness abroad. Greek merchant families already possessed established networks in other countries, and during the period of unrest, many relocated to centers around the Mediterranean (notably Marseilles in [France](/Greeks_in_France), Livorno in [Italy](/Greeks_in_Italy), Alexandria in [Egypt](/Greeks_in_Egypt)), [Russia](/Greeks_in_Russia) ([Odesa](/Odesa) and [Saint Petersburg](/Saint_Petersburg)), and [Britain](/British_Greeks) (London and Liverpool), where they engaged in trade, primarily in textiles and grain. Businesses were often organized around extended family units, and with them, they brought Greek schools and the [Greek Orthodox Church](/Greek_Orthodox_Church). As markets evolved and their enterprises grew more established, some families expanded their operations into shipping, financed through local Greek communities, notably with the assistance of the [Ralli Brothers](/Ralli_Brothers) or the [Vagliano Brothers](/Panayis_Athanase_Vagliano). With economic success, the Diaspora expanded further, reaching across the [Levant](/Greeks_in_Syria), North Africa, India, and the USA.

In the 20th century, numerous Greeks emigrated from their traditional homelands for economic reasons, leading to significant migrations from Greece and Cyprus to the [United States](/Greek_American), [Great Britain](/Greeks_in_the_United_Kingdom), [Australia](/Greek_Australian), [Canada](/Greek_Canadian), [Germany](/Greeks_in_Germany), and [South Africa](/Greeks_in_South_Africa), particularly after the [Second World War](/Second_World_War) (1939–1945), the [Greek Civil War](/Greek_Civil_War) (1946–1949), and the [Turkish Invasion of Cyprus](/Turkish_Invasion_of_Cyprus) in 1974.

While official figures remain limited, polls and anecdotal evidence suggest a resurgence of Greek emigration as a consequence of the [Greek financial crisis](/Greek_financial_crisis). According to data released by the [Federal Statistical Office of Germany](/Federal_Statistical_Office_of_Germany) in 2011, 23,800 Greeks emigrated to Germany, marking a substantial increase compared to the preceding year. In contrast, approximately 9,000 Greeks emigrated to Germany in 2009 and 12,000 in 2010.

***

### Culture

[Greek culture](/Culture_of_Greece) has evolved over millennia, originating in the Mycenaean civilization and continuing through the classical era, the Hellenistic period, and the Roman and Byzantine periods. It was profoundly shaped by Christianity, which it, in turn, influenced and molded. [Ottoman Greeks](/Ottoman_Greeks) endured centuries of hardship, culminating in [genocide](/Greek_genocide) during the 20th century. The [Diafotismos](/Diafotismos) movement is credited with revitalizing Greek culture and fostering the synthesis of ancient and medieval elements that characterize it today.

#### Language

The majority of Greeks speak the [Greek language](/Greek_language), an [independent branch](/Hellenic_languages) of the [Indo-European languages](/Indo-European_languages), with its closest relatives possibly being [Armenian](/Armenian_language) (see [Graeco-Armenian](/Graeco-Armenian)) or the [Indo-Iranian languages](/Indo-Iranian_languages) (see [Graeco-Aryan](/Graeco-Aryan)). It possesses the longest documented history of any living language, and [Greek literature](/Greek_literature) has a continuous tradition spanning over 2,500 years. The earliest inscriptions in Greek are found in the [Linear B](/Linear_B) script, dating back to 1450 BC. Following the [Greek Dark Ages](/Greek_Dark_Ages), a period devoid of written records, the [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet) emerged in the 9th–8th century BC. The Greek alphabet, derived from the [Phoenician alphabet](/Phoenician_alphabet), subsequently became the progenitor of the [Latin](/Latin), [Cyrillic](/Cyrillic), and several other alphabets. The earliest Greek literary works are the [Homeric epics](/Homer), variously dated from the 8th to the 6th century BC. Notable scientific and mathematical contributions include Euclid's [Elements](/Euclid%27s_Elements), Ptolemy's [Almagest](/Almagest), and other works. The [New Testament](/New_Testament) was originally written in [Koine Greek](/Koine_Greek).

Greek exhibits several linguistic features shared with other [Balkan languages](/Languages_of_the_Balkans), such as [Albanian](/Albanian_language), [Bulgarian](/Bulgarian_language), and [Eastern Romance languages](/Eastern_Romance_languages) (forming part of the [Balkan sprachbund](/Balkan_sprachbund)). It has also absorbed numerous foreign words, primarily from Western European and [Turkish](/Turkish_language) origins. Due to the influence of [Philhellenism](/Philhellenism) and the [Diafotismos](/Diafotismos) movement in the 19th century, which emphasized the modern Greeks' connection to their ancient heritage, these foreign influences were largely excluded from official usage through the development of [Katharevousa](/Katharevousa). This was a somewhat artificial form of Greek purged of foreign influences and words, serving as the official language of the Greek state. However, in 1976, the [Hellenic Parliament](/Hellenic_Parliament) legislated to make the spoken [Dimotiki](/Dimotiki) the official language, rendering Katharevousa obsolete.

[Modern Greek](/Modern_Greek), in addition to Standard Modern Greek (Dimotiki), encompasses a wide array of dialects with varying degrees of mutual intelligibility. These include [Cypriot](/Cypriot_Greek), [Pontic](/Pontic_language), [Cappadocian](/Cappadocian_Greek), [Griko](/Griko_language), and [Tsakonian](/Tsakonian_language) (the sole surviving representative of ancient [Doric Greek](/Doric_Greek)). [Yevanic](/Yevanic_language) is the language of the [Romaniotes](/Romaniotes) and persists in small communities in Greece, New York, and Israel. Beyond Greek, many Greek citizens, both within Greece and in the diaspora, are bilingual in other languages such as English, [Arvanitika](/Arvanitika)/Albanian, [Aromanian](/Aromanian_language), [Megleno-Romanian](/Megleno-Romanian_language), [Macedonian Slavic](/Slavic_dialects_of_Greece), [Russian](/Russian_language), and Turkish.

#### Religion

The majority of Greeks are [Christians](/Christians), adhering to the [Greek Orthodox Church](/Greek_Orthodox_Church). During the early centuries following the life of [Jesus Christ](/Jesus), the [New Testament](/New_Testament) was originally written in [Koine Greek](/Koine_Greek), which continues to serve as the [liturgical language](/Sacred_language) of the Greek Orthodox Church. Most early Christians and Church Fathers were Greek speakers. Small groups of ethnic Greeks adhere to other [Christian](/Christianity) denominations, including [Latin](/Latin_Church) and [Greek Byzantine](/Greek_Byzantine_Catholic_Church) [Catholics](/Catholic_Church), [Greek Evangelicals](/Greek_Evangelical_Church), [Pentecostals](/Free_Apostolic_Church_of_Pentecost), and [Mormons](/Mormons). There are also communities adhering to other religions, such as [Romaniot](/Romaniotes) and [Sephardic Jews](/Sephardic_Jews), [Greek Muslims](/Greek_Muslims), and [Jehovah's Witnesses](/Jehovah%27s_Witnesses). Approximately 2,000 Greeks are members of [Hellenic Polytheistic Reconstructionism](/Hellenic_Polytheistic_Reconstructionism) congregations.

Greek-speaking Muslims are primarily found outside Greece in contemporary times. Both Christian and Muslim Greek-speaking communities exist in [Lebanon](/Greeks_in_Lebanon) and [Syria](/Greeks_in_Syria). In the [Pontus](/Pontus_(region)) region of [Turkey](/Turkey), there is a sizable community of indeterminate size who were exempted from the [population exchange](/Population_exchange_between_Greece_and_Turkey) due to their religious affiliation.

#### Arts

[Greek art](/Greek_art) boasts a long and diverse history, with Greeks contributing significantly to the visual, literary, and performing arts. In the Western world, [classical Greek art](/Art_in_ancient_Greece) exerted a profound influence on the development of [Roman](/Roman_art) and subsequent modern [Western artistic heritage](/Western_art_history). Throughout the [Renaissance](/Renaissance) in [Europe](/Europe), the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists. For centuries, the classical tradition derived from Greece played a pivotal role in Western art. In the East, the conquests of [Alexander the Great](/Alexander_the_Great) initiated centuries of cultural exchange between Greek, [Central Asian](/Central_Asia), and [Indian](/Culture_of_India) civilizations, resulting in [Indo-Greek](/Indo-Greek_art) and [Greco-Buddhist art](/Greco-Buddhist_art), whose influence extended as far as [Japan](/Japan).

[Byzantine Greek art](/Byzantine_art), which evolved from Hellenistic [classical art](/Fayum_portrait) and adapted pagan motifs for Christian purposes, provided inspiration for the art of numerous nations. Its influences can be traced from [Venice](/Venice) in the west to [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan) in the east. Conversely, Greek art was also influenced by eastern civilizations (e.g., [Egypt](/Art_of_ancient_Egypt), [Persia](/Persian_art), etc.) during various periods of its history.

Notable modern Greek artists include:

*   Painters such as [Dominikos Theotokopoulos](/Dominikos_Theotokopoulos) (El Greco), [Nikolaos Gyzis](/Nikolaos_Gyzis), [Konstantinos Volanakis](/Konstantinos_Volanakis), [Périclès Pantazis](/P%C3%A9ricl%C3%A8s_Pantazis), and [Constantine Andreou](/Constantine_Andreou); sculptors like [Yannoulis Chalepas](/Yannoulis_Chalepas).
*   Composers such as [Mikis Theodorakis](/Mikis_Theodorakis), [Spyridon Samaras](/Spyridon_Samaras), [Iannis Xenakis](/Iannis_Xenakis), [Yanni](/Yanni), and [Vangelis](/Vangelis).
*   Singers such as [Maria Callas](/Maria_Callas), [Giorgos Dalaras](/Giorgos_Dalaras), [Nana Mouskouri](/Nana_Mouskouri), [Vicky Leandros](/Vicky_Leandros), and [Demis Roussos](/Demis_Roussos).
*   Poets including [Dionysios Solomos](/Dionysios_Solomos), [Angelos Sikelianos](/Angelos_Sikelianos), [Andreas Embirikos](/Andreas_Embirikos), [Constantine P. Cavafy](/Constantine_P._Cavafy), and Nobel laureates [Giorgos Seferis](/Giorgos_Seferis) and [Odysseas Elytis](/Odysseas_Elytis).
*   Novelists such as [Alexandros Papadiamantis](/Alexandros_Papadiamantis), [Emmanuel Rhoides](/Emmanuel_Rhoides), [Ion Dragoumis](/Ion_Dragoumis), [Nikos Kazantzakis](/Nikos_Kazantzakis), [Penelope Delta](/Penelope_Delta), [Stratis Myrivilis](/Stratis_Myrivilis), [Vassilis Vassilikos](/Vassilis_Vassilikos), and [Petros Markaris](/Petros_Markaris).
*   Playwrights, including the [Cretan Renaissance](/Cretan_Renaissance) poets [Georgios Chortatzis](/Georgios_Chortatzis) and [Vincenzos Cornaros](/Vitsentzos_Kornaros), as well as [Gregorios Xenopoulos](/Gregorios_Xenopoulos) and [Iakovos Kambanellis](/Iakovos_Kambanellis).

[Eleftherios Venizelos](/Eleftherios_Venizelos) was a pivotal political figure in 20th-century Greece.

Renowned actors in cinema and theatre include [Marika Kotopouli](/Marika_Kotopouli), [Melina Mercouri](/Melina_Mercouri), [Ellie Lambeti](/Ellie_Lambeti), Academy Award winner [Katina Paxinou](/Katina_Paxinou), [Alexis Minotis](/Alexis_Minotis), [Dimitris Horn](/Dimitris_Horn), [Thanasis Veggos](/Thanasis_Veggos), [Manos Katrakis](/Manos_Katrakis), and [Irene Papas](/Irene_Papas). Among the most influential directors are [Alekos Sakellarios](/Alekos_Sakellarios), [Karolos Koun](/Karolos_Koun), [Vasilis Georgiadis](/Vasilis_Georgiadis), [Kostas Gavras](/Costa-Gavras), [Michael Cacoyannis](/Michael_Cacoyannis), [Giannis Dalianidis](/Giannis_Dalianidis), [Nikos Koundouros](/Nikos_Koundouros), and [Theo Angelopoulos](/Theo_Angelopoulos).

Leading architects of the modern era include [Stamatios Kleanthis](/Stamatios_Kleanthis), [Lysandros Kaftanzoglou](/Lysandros_Kaftanzoglou), [Anastasios Metaxas](/Anastasios_Metaxas), [Panagis Kalkos](/Panagis_Kalkos), [Anastasios Orlandos](/Anastasios_Orlandos), the naturalized Greek [Ernst Ziller](/Ernst_Ziller), [Dimitris Pikionis](/Dimitris_Pikionis), and urban planners [Stamatis Voulgaris](/Stamatis_Voulgaris) and [George Candilis](/George_Candilis).

#### Science

The Greeks of the Classical and Hellenistic eras made foundational contributions to science and philosophy, establishing the groundwork for numerous Western scientific traditions, including [astronomy](/Greek_astronomy), [geography](/Geography), [historiography](/Historiography), [mathematics](/Greek_mathematics), [medicine](/Greek_medicine), [philosophy](/Greek_philosophy), and [political science](/Political_science). The scholarly tradition of Greek academies was sustained throughout Roman times, with several institutions flourishing in centers of Greek learning such as [Constantinople](/Constantinople), [Antioch](/Antioch), and [Alexandria](/Alexandria). Byzantine science essentially represented a continuation of classical science. Greeks have historically placed a high value on and invested significantly in *paideia* (education). *Paideia* was considered one of the highest societal values in the Greek and Hellenistic worlds. The first institution in Europe recognized as a university was established in 5th-century Constantinople and operated in various forms until the city's fall to the Ottomans in 1453. The [University of Constantinople](/University_of_Constantinople) was Europe's first secular institution of higher learning, as it did not offer theological subjects, and considering the original meaning of "university" as a corporation of students, it can be considered the world's first university.

As of 2007, Greece ranked eighth globally in terms of tertiary enrollment percentages (with female student enrollment exceeding that of males). Greeks in the diaspora are equally active in the field of education. Hundreds of thousands of Greek students attend Western universities annually, and the faculty lists of leading Western universities prominently feature a significant number of Greek names. Notable Greek scientists of modern times include: physician [Georgios Papanicolaou](/Georgios_Papanikolaou) (a pioneer in [cytopathology](/Cytopathology) and inventor of the [Pap test](/Pap_test)); mathematician [Constantin Carathéodory](/Constantin_Carath%C3%A9odory) (acclaimed contributor to real and complex analysis and the calculus of variations); archaeologists [Manolis Andronikos](/Manolis_Andronikos) (who unearthed the tomb of [Philip II of Macedon](/Philip_II_of_Macedon)), [Valerios Stais](/Valerios_Stais) (who recognized the [Antikythera mechanism](/Antikythera_mechanism)), [Spyridon Marinatos](/Spyridon_Marinatos) (specializing in [Mycenaean](/Mycenaean_Greece) sites), and [Ioannis Svoronos](/Ioannis_Svoronos); chemists [Leonidas Zervas](/Leonidas_Zervas) (known for the [Bergmann-Zervas synthesis](/Bergmann-Zervas_carbobenzoxy_method) and the discovery of the [Z-group](/Z-group)), [K. C. Nicolaou](/K._C._Nicolaou) (who achieved the first total synthesis of [taxol](/Paclitaxel)), and [Panayotis Katsoyannis](/Panayotis_Katsoyannis) (who performed the first chemical synthesis of [insulin](/Insulin)); computer scientists [Michael Dertouzos](/Michael_Dertouzos) and [Nicholas Negroponte](/Nicholas_Negroponte) (recognized for their early work on the [World Wide Web](/World_Wide_Web)), [John Argyris](/John_Argyris) (co-creator of the [FEM](/Finite_element_method)), [Joseph Sifakis](/Joseph_Sifakis) (recipient of the 2007 [Turing Award](/Turing_Award)), [Christos Papadimitriou](/Christos_Papadimitriou) (recipient of the 2002 [Knuth Prize](/Knuth_Prize)), and [Mihalis Yannakakis](/Mihalis_Yannakakis) (recipient of the 2005 [Knuth Prize](/Knuth_Prize)); physicist-mathematician [Demetrios Christodoulou](/Demetrios_Christodoulou) (renowned for his work on [Minkowski spacetime](/Minkowski_spacetime)) and physicists [Achilles Papapetrou](/Achilles_Papapetrou) (known for solutions in [general relativity](/General_relativity)), [Dimitri Nanopoulos](/Dimitri_Nanopoulos) (with extensive work on particle physics and cosmology), and [John Iliopoulos](/John_Iliopoulos) (recipient of the 2007 [Dirac Medal (ICTP)](/Dirac_Medal_(ICTP)) for his contributions to [charm quark](/Charm_quark) research); astronomer [Eugenios Antoniadis](/E._M._Antoniadi); biologist [Fotis Kafatos](/Fotis_Kafatos) (a contributor to [cDNA](/CDNA) cloning technology); botanist [Theodoros Orphanides](/Theodoros_G._Orphanides); economist [Xenophon Zolotas](/Xenophon_Zolotas) (who held various senior positions in international organizations such as the [IMF](/International_Monetary_Fund)); Indologist [Dimitrios Galanos](/Dimitrios_Galanos); linguist [Yiannis Psycharis](/Ioannis_Psycharis) (a proponent of [Demotic Greek](/Demotic_Greek)); historians [Constantine Paparrigopoulos](/Constantine_Paparrigopoulos) (founder of modern Greek historiography) and [Helene Glykatzi Ahrweiler](/Helene_Ahrweiler) (distinguished in [Byzantine studies](/Byzantine_studies)); and political scientists [Nicos Poulantzas](/Nicos_Poulantzas) (a leading [Structural Marxist](/Structural_Marxism)) and [Cornelius Castoriadis](/Cornelius_Castoriadis) (philosopher of history, ontologist, social critic, economist, and psychoanalyst).

Notable engineers and automotive designers include [Nikolas Tombazis](/Nikolas_Tombazis), [Alec Issigonis](/Alec_Issigonis), and [Andreas Zapatinas](/Andreas_Zapatinas).

