### Politics

[Classical Athens](/Classical_Athens) is widely considered the birthplace of [Democracy](/Democracy). The term emerged in the 5th century BC to describe the political systems prevalent in [Greek city-states](/Greek_city-state), particularly Athens, signifying "rule of the people," in contrast to [aristocracy](/Aristocracy) (*aristokratía*, meaning "rule by an excellent elite") and [oligarchy](/Oligarchy). While these definitions were theoretically distinct, the historical application has often blurred the lines. Led by [Cleisthenes](/Cleisthenes), Athenians established what is generally regarded as the first democracy in 508–507 BC, which gradually evolved into a form of [direct democracy](/Direct_democracy). The democratic form of government declined during the Hellenistic and Roman eras, only to be revived and garner renewed interest in Western Europe during the [early modern period](/Early_modern_period).

The European Enlightenment and the democratic, liberal, and nationalistic ideals of the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution) proved to be crucial factors in precipitating the [Greek War of Independence](/Greek_War_of_Independence) and the subsequent establishment of the modern Greek state. Notable modern Greek politicians include [Ioannis Kapodistrias](/Ioannis_Kapodistrias), the founder of the [First Hellenic Republic](/First_Hellenic_Republic); the reformist [Charilaos Trikoupis](/Charilaos_Trikoupis); [Eleftherios Venizelos](/Eleftherios_Venizelos), who significantly shaped modern Greece; the social democrats [Georgios Papandreou](/Georgios_Papandreou) and [Alexandros Papanastasiou](/Alexandros_Papanastasiou); [Konstantinos Karamanlis](/Konstantinos_Karamanlis), the founder of the [Third Hellenic Republic](/Third_Hellenic_Republic); and the socialist [Andreas Papandreou](/Andreas_Papandreou).

